<DIV>Thanks, Eric.&nbsp; </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>I think the main update is that we have pretty high confidence that we =
could put a 100 acre solar farm on site, which would require no public cash, =
loans or otherwise.&nbsp; At a minimum of&nbsp;25 megawatts, I suspect that =
would be one of the largest if not the largest in Delaware.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>As with the Green Diesel project, meeting the Treasury Department's =
"substantially underway" by 12/31/2010 test is mandatory.&nbsp; I assume that =
interest is aligned withe the Governor, since job creation sooner is much =
better than later.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>After Hunter has a chance to chat with the Gov, let's do a quick call to =
understand his view of how attractive either/both of these projects are.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Hunter, I know you may not have to/want to get into every detail on the =
first call, but here's a quick checklist of things we need to make each project =
a go, in case you get asked:</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Solar Power Plant:</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>1.&nbsp; 100 acres land granted to us, or a 99-year $1.00/year =
lease.</DIV>
<DIV>2.&nbsp; Access to the grid inter-connect that we understand exists at the =
power plant on site</DIV>
<DIV>3.&nbsp; Ordinary rates and Solar Renewable Energy Credits under DE =
regs</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Green Diesel Plant:</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>1.&nbsp; $25-50m in preferred-payback loans from DE Economic Development =
Commission or in investment from Valero (or any other ITC-qualified investor) =
to retrofit old equipment or build new equipment on site</DIV>
<DIV>2.&nbsp; 20 acres of land granted to us, or $1/year 25 year lease</DIV>
<DIV>3.&nbsp; Access to existing infrastructure at the site (power, port berth, =
etc.)</DIV>
<DIV>4.&nbsp; Permits to build a truck-turnaround for 18-wheelers<BR></DIV>
<DIV>Both projects would bring substantial new hard hat jobs during =
construction, as well as permanent operating jobs post-generation.&nbsp; The =
Green Diesel project has more permanent jobs than any solar farm, plus the =
obvious additonal jobs for truckers, pipefitters, longshoremen, operating =
engineers, laborers, tug-boat operators, etc etc.<BR></DIV>
<DIV>Happy to discuss any time today/tomorrow as helpful.&nbsp; Pls use my cell =
over the weekend, 415-235-0700.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
